title: For Sale/Trade:  Who Are These Idiots?  Part V
postcontent:
--Trying to sell a gun with out-of-focus pics or no photo at all.
(And everyone's all-time pisser, the UPSIDE DOWN photos.)
--Just because your AR-15 has optics and an after-market grip does not make it a "custom" rifle.
--Most of us know one Generation of Glock from another, but as a courtesy go ahead and provide that info.
--Another courtesy is to list the year of manufacture for your firearms.
--Most buyers need and want more than just "Winchester 30-30" in the description. Is it an XTR, Ranger, Commemorative? Year of manufacture?  Pre-64?
--Why are you asking more for your gun that what I can buy a new one for?
--A Llama 45ACP is not worth $450 no matter what you think.
--Know your AR-15 chambers. Is it .223 Rem, 5.56 NATO, or .223 Wylde?
--A 1, 2, 5, 10, or 20 year old gun is not "new" whether it's been fired or not.
--Just because you built it does not make it worth more.
--Know the difference between "rare" and "hard to find."
--If you are charging more than 8 cents per round for 22LR, you are part of the problem and not part of the solution.  Same for more than 40 CPR for 5.56 and 45ACP, 30 CPR for 9MM...
--Is your FN Five seveN a MK2 or Mk1?  Know your Marks and Mods.
--Using "pre-ban" is really not necessary as there is no longer a ban in effect.

...and finally...A Glock costs $500 and comes with two mags (G3) or three mags (G4.)  Just because you pay tax and background fees does not mean you pass it along to buyers on Armslist.  More mags and ammo will get you more money, but remember, its a USED gun nonetheless--whether you fired it or not.  There really are no "rare" Glocks out there and "custom" work is questionable at best.  Good luck.

title: For Sale:  Bushmaster M4 5.56/.223 with EOTech, Magpul accessories and sling plus Nickel-Boron internals
postcontent: Selling my Bushmaster Carbon 15 M4. It is stamped 5.56 so you can shoot that or .223 from this weapon. Started off stock then I re did the whole body with Magpul furniture to include the MOE hand guard and vertical grip, the ACS friction lock stock, the MIAD pistol grip, the ASAP backplate/swivel sling mount, and the Magpul dynamics ASAP 2/1 point sling with the front anchor mount on the hand guard. It also has folding iron sights and a railed gas block and the "izzy" compensator/flash suppressor and the BCM gunfighter charging handle. The sight is an EOTech 516 which takes AA batteries and has the raised battery case so you can mount it as far forward as you wish. On the inside we have the Spike's Tactical Nickel-Boron bolt and bolt carrier group as well as the same brand and finish trigger group for a smooth feel and break. It is a self lubricating metal and I have never had to put a drop of CLP/lubricant inside when firing. It also is unbelievably simple to clean. The carbon does not stick to it the way it does to a normal phosphate coated bolt and is as simple as wiping it off with a cleaning rag. It also operated well in sandy conditions as there is no lubricant to mix with dirt/sand to gunk up the weapon. Dumped sand in the chamber, racked it, and it still blew through a whole mag like the dirt wasn't there. I bought the weapon new in 2012 and have been upgrading it as I went along. I am a prior service Marine and can say I wish that our weapons had the internals this thing does! A dealer put the value of the weapon at $1400, but it can be yours today for $1200!

title: For Sale:  Hydro Dipping
postcontent:
WELCOME TO OUTDOOR ARMOR 
Your Custom Hydrographic Shop

Wondering what Hydrographics is?  Hydrographics is a method of applying printed designs to three-dimensional objects.  The hydrographic process can be used on metal, plastic, glass, hard woods, and various other materials. In the process, first the substrate piece to be printed is prepared/primed and a base coat material is applied. Second the pre-printed film with the graphic image to be transferred is then floated on the surface of a tank of water. An activator chemical is sprayed on the film to dissolve it into a liquid and activate a bonding agent. The piece is then lowered into the tank, through the floating ink layer, which wraps around and adheres to it.  After removing the piece from the water it is placed in a wash tank where all the excess material and residue is washed off.  Last, once the piece is dry a clear coat is applied to protect the design. With multiple dippings, hydrographics printing can achieve full 360° coverage of the part surface, including small crevices.


Here at Outdoor Armor we take pride in creating one of kind projects to meet all aspects in life from, Hunting and Fishing, to Motorcycle Riders, to Custom Car Builders, to Home Decor. title: For Sale:  1939 M91/30 Tula Mosin Nagant w/ extras
postcontent:
This is a 1939 tula manufactured Mosin Nagant M91/30.  It is in excellent condition, actually it's better than when it was new. this rifle has been fully restored and it operates and fires flawlessly.  The stock of the rifle is truly unique with small knot marks that are random throughout the stock. I think the wood stock made in England from chestnut possibly.  The barrel is cosmetically smooth to the finish and does not seem to have poor machining done to it like other typical M91/30's.  The bore is excellent and the rifle is very accurate. All of the rest of the metal is in great condition with good blueing. All the numbers match except the floor plate which was force matched no doubt by the Russians during the refurbishment process earlier in the rifles life. This rifle comes with the following.  

1 padded rifle case (soft zip up type)
1 rifle sling With dog collars. (New) 
1 oiler (original)
1 original surplus rifle cleaning kit
1 new rifle cleaning kit w/ rod and new brushes etc...

500 rounds of 7.62x54r  ( mostly surplus ). 40 or so new production fmj

title: For Sale/Trade:  Frigon/Marocchi 12 gauge Trap Gun
postcontent:
Up for sale, I have a 12 gauge Frigon, which is a re-badged Marocchi imported by a prominent trap shooter named Frenchy Firgon.  It is a Frigon Trap Combo and it fires Bottom Barrel First.  It fires the top barrel in sequence.  There is no barrel selector.  There is no ability to fire the top barrel first.  

There is a second single barrel.  It is a top single and there is the problem!  The gun was made as a top first firing gun, but was modified to fire bottom first.  Therefore, it doesn't really function as a combo.  As such it is being sold as an Over/Under.  Both barrels are ported.

9/8: If this gun doesn't sell this week, the ad will come down and the gun will be sent off to the gunsmith so it will fire top-first.  When it comes back, it will be sold as a combo and the price is going to nearly double.  Buy now and get a bargain or buy later and pay what it's worth.

It isn't perfect.  It has dings in the stock here and there, but it is a great shooting gun.   It points well and hits hard.  It's better than an entry level gun, but it lacks a few things that my son requires as his trap shooting progresses.  I am not interested in Hi-Points or .22's.

I just took this gun out on 10/4 and shot sporting clays.  Despite the O/U barrels being longer than most, it still allowed me to hit both birds.

10/24: Heard back from the gunsmith.  He finally got around to my gun and tells me that it's an easy (inexpensive) fix.  Unfortunately, he's backlogged and probably won't get to it until mid to late November.  If I get a buyer before he fixes it, they'll get a bargain.  Once he has it fixed, I will replace this ad and charge book value.  (if you've looked it up, you can see how much of a bargain this is.

title: For Trade:  Non-import marked Soviet Russian Makarov - GI bring back
postcontent:
I have a 1976, non-import marked Soviet Russian Makarov (PM) pistol I'm willing to entertain trade offers on. The gun saw action in the 1979-1989 Soviet Invasion of Afghanistan and was obtained in Saudi Arabia in 1991 by a US service member stationed there during Desert Storm/Desert Shield and brought home under the radar. As such it is not import marked. The gun is in excellent functional condition mechanically with a bright bore with crisp rifling. Cosmetically, the gun has light battlefield wear to the bluing and very light micro-pitting on the slide from previous exposure to the elements. This is the real deal and not a surplus gun. Included with the gun is a Soviet Military holster, lanyard and cleaning rod that I tracked down from a gentleman in Kherson, Ukraine. He shipped it to me from Kherson with the Russians practically on his doorstep during the annexation of Crimea. I have the shipping box and the customs declaration form with it. Also included with the gun is a Soviet Medal Internationalist and the Afghan campaign medal awarded to Russian soldiers who participated in the Soviet invasion, complete with signed award documentation paperwork. To top it off, I have the gun in a custom Cold War Era presentation briefcase with Soviet insignia. I'll also throw in a Leningrad pin as a bonus. The gun has two spare Russian mags. I also have some aftermarket Makarov accessories such as additional mags, some ammo and grips that are non-collectible that I can throw in as well.

I would value this Soviet collection at around $1,500 - $1,800. I am entertaining trade offers in that approximate value range. It is currently listed on gunbroker as well:

title: For Sale:  S&W Model 27-2 "N" frame, .357 Magnum 3 1/2" barrel
postcontent:
Selling my beautiful .357. My brother bought it new, and I believe that was in the early 1980's. I inherited it when he passed away. 

Serial number is N200XXX. It has a pinned barrel, and that mirror polished beautiful blue that S&W used to care enough to do. When I got the gun it was unfired. Brother liked to collect more than shoot. I have run 450 rounds of .38 special thru it. So 450 rounds in over 30 years. And it looks it. Condition is easily 99%+. 

This revolver has NEVER been modified or molested in any way. No hack trigger jobs, no lighter springs. Never even taken apart at all, Just shot, cleaned, and stored. I am more of a semi-auto lover, but this thing I have hung on to for years because it is so beautiful, and the action is so sweet. But now I have my sights set on a very badass AR-10, so selling things I don't absolutely have to have. 

It comes with original box, original newspaper clipping of the ad from Rocky Mountain News (Dave Cook I think, but can't swear to. Might have been Gart's), original warranty registration(never completed) and a S&W brochure on holster they were selling at the time. 

I also have a Crimson Trace laser grip for the gun, and a Hogue Monogrip I will throw in. I bought the laser grip thinking my wife might like to use the gun as a home defense weapon. But she found it too heavy. I guess an "N" frame is pretty stout, but that is what makes them so nice to shoot. No pleasing women though. 

Price is firm. I have seen lesser versions sell for this or more (Cabela's south this morning in fact), and they did not come with laser grips. As I said, I really love this revolver and don't have to sell. I would LIKE to sell just to spend a bunch more money on another toy. But can live with keeping it. 

Any questions, please just ask. And as far as meeting to show or sell, it will be in a public place where you are safe, and more importantly, I am safe. And all Colorado laws will be followed concerning transferring ownership. I hate it, but not going to jail just because our governor(soon to be ex) is a dumbass, among dumbasses. 

Only exception would be if the transfer happened to take place in a neighboring state that does not require background checks for private sales.
